## 📈 Dashboard Components

### KPI Cards — At a Glance
| Metric | Value |
|---|---|
| Average Salary of Survey Takers | **$53.36K** |
| Total Survey Respondents | **630** |
| Average Age of Survey Takers | **29.87 years** |

### Country of Respondents — Treemap
Geographic breakdown of where survey takers are based. The **United States** leads with 261 respondents, followed by **India** at 73, with the remaining distributed across UK, Canada, and other regions.

### Average Salary by Job Title — Horizontal Bar Chart
Salary comparison across data roles:

| Job Title | Avg. Salary |
|---|---|
| Data Scientist | **88** |
| Data Architect | 64 |
| Data Engineer | 61 |
| Other | 60 |
| Data Analyst | 55 |
| Database Developer | 33 |
| Student / Looking | 27 |

> Data Scientists earn the highest average salary — 60% more than Data Analysts and more than 3x students/job seekers.

### Favourite Programming Language — Bar Chart
Python is the overwhelming favourite across all job titles, far ahead of R, SQL, C/C++, JavaScript, and Java. The chart is broken down by job title (Data Analyst, Data Architect, Data Engineer) to show role-specific preferences.

### Happiness with Work/Life Balance — Gauge Chart
**5.74 / 10** — Survey takers rate their work/life balance slightly above the midpoint, suggesting moderate but not strong satisfaction.

### Happiness with Salary — Gauge Chart
**4.27 / 10** — Salary satisfaction scores below the midpoint, indicating that a majority of data professionals feel underpaid relative to expectations — despite the profession's reputation for high compensation.

### Difficulty to Break into Data — Donut Chart
| Difficulty Level | Share |
|---|---|
| Neither Easy nor Difficult | 41.61% |
| Difficult | 24.76% |
| Very Difficult | 23.58% |
| Easy | 5.00% |
| Very Easy | 5.00% |

> Nearly **48%** of respondents found breaking into data difficult or very difficult — a key insight for anyone planning a career transition.

---

## 🔍 Key Findings

- **Data Scientists** earn the most on average, but even they rate salary satisfaction at below 5/10 — suggesting industry compensation expectations outpace actual pay
- **Python** dominates as the preferred language across all data roles with no close second
- **Work/life balance (5.74)** scores higher than salary satisfaction **(4.27)** — professionals are more content with their hours than their pay
- Almost **half of all respondents** found entering the data field difficult or very difficult, reinforcing that a strong portfolio and certifications matter
- The **US dominates** the respondent pool (41%), meaning salary benchmarks skew toward US market rates

